div.span:
Catching a specific exception is generally considered better practice because it allows for more targeted error handling. If you catch a specific exception, you can provide more precise error messages and take appropriate actions to handle that particular exception.
On the other hand, catching a more general exception like Exception may be appropriate if you don't know what specific exceptions might be thrown in your code. However, catching a more general exception could mask important errors if you're not careful.
So, both ways are correct, but it's generally better to catch specific exceptions whenever possible.

div.span: Rethrowing an exception means catching an exception in one part of the code and then throwing it again so that it can be handled by another part of the code. This is typically done when an exception is caught at a lower level of the code but needs to be handled by higher-level code that has more context or information about how to handle the exception.

div.span: In Java, "try-with-resources" is a language construct that was introduced in Java 7 to help automatically manage the resources used by the program.

div.style: user-select: none; --webkit-user-select:none; line-height: normal; overflow: visible; white-space: break-spaces; overflow-wrap: break-word; text-overflow: clip; font-family: "Yrsa SemiBold", Roboto, NeverMind, sans-serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 600; color: rgb(0, 102, 66); text-align: left; text-decoration: none;
div.span: When you use try-with-resources, you declare one or more resources (such as input/output streams, database connections, sockets, etc.) that are automatically closed at the end of the block. This means that you don't have to manually close these resources yourself, which can help prevent resource leaks and simplify your code.

div.span: The resources used in a try-with-resources block must implement the AutoCloseable interface. This includes many common Java types, such as InputStream, OutputStream, Reader, Writer, and more.

div.span: When creating a user-defined exception in Java, you can choose to extend either the RuntimeException class or the Exception class. However, there is a key difference between these two approaches.

div.span: If you extend the RuntimeException class, you are creating an unchecked exception. Unchecked exceptions do not need to be declared in a method's throws clause and can be caught or propagated up the call stack like any other exception

div.span: However, it is generally recommended that you use unchecked exceptions sparingly, as they can lead to unexpected behavior if not used carefully.

div.span: Alternatively, if you extend the Exception class, you are creating a checked exception. Checked exceptions must be declared in a method's throws clause, and callers of that method must either handle the exception or declare it in their own throws clause.

div.span: 1-Use checked exceptions for recoverable conditions and runtime exceptions for programming errors.

div.style: user-select: none; --webkit-user-select:none; line-height: normal; overflow: visible; white-space: break-spaces; overflow-wrap: break-word; text-overflow: clip; font-family: "Yrsa SemiBold", Roboto, NeverMind, sans-serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 600; color: rgb(28, 26, 75); text-align: left; text-decoration: none;
div.span:
Checked exceptions are used to indicate recoverable conditions, such as input/output errors and network failures, which might occur during the normal operation of a program. By forcing the caller to handle these exceptions, checked exceptions provide a way for the program to recover from these types of errors.
On the other hand, runtime exceptions are used to indicate programming errors, such as null pointer dereferences and array index out of bounds errors, which can usually be prevented by better coding practices. These types of exceptions are often not recoverable and can cause the program to terminate abruptly if they are not handled properly.
By using checked exceptions for recoverable conditions and runtime exceptions for programming errors, you can help ensure that your code is more robust and handles exceptions in a consistent and predictable way.

div.span: 2-Don't ignore exceptions, always handle them explicitly.

div.span: 3-Avoid using exception handling for flow control.

div.style: user-select: none; --webkit-user-select:none; line-height: normal; overflow: visible; white-space: break-spaces; overflow-wrap: break-word; text-overflow: clip; font-family: "Yrsa SemiBold", Roboto, NeverMind, sans-serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 600; color: rgb(28, 26, 75); text-align: left; text-decoration: none;
div.span:
It is generally considered a bad programming practice to use exception handling for flow control. Exceptions should be used only for exceptional conditions that cannot be handled in the normal flow of the program. Using exceptions for flow control can make code more difficult to read and can slow down performance.
Instead of using exceptions for flow control, it is better to use conditional statements such as if-else or switch-case statements. These statements are designed for flow control and can be used to handle different cases and execute different blocks of code depending on certain conditions.
By using conditional statements instead of exceptions for flow control, you can make your code more clear and efficient, and reduce the likelihood of unexpected errors or bugs.
